Bring a medium #pot{} (large pot for 4 servings) of @salted water{} to a boil. Wash
and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Zest and quarter
@lime{1}.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}, then drain.

While noodles cook, open package of chicken* and drain off any excess liquid.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels. Swap in
> shrimp for chicken.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pan{} over
medium-high heat. Add @shrimp{10%ounce} and broccoli; season with
@garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until shrimp is browned and cooked through and broccoli is tender,
~{4-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If your broccoli isn't bright green after 2-3 minutes, cover the pan to
> help it cook!

Remove pan from heat. Add @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, @sweet Thai chili
sauce{1%ounce}, @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings), and as many
@?Korean chili flakes{1%teaspoon} as you like (we used ½ tsp; 1 tsp for 4);
stir to combine.

To pan with shrimp and broccoli, add drained noodles, lime zest, and juice from
half the lime; toss to coat. Taste and season with @salt{}.

Divide shrimp lo mein between shallow #bowls{}. Serve with remaining lime
wedges on the side.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.